paragraphs.title: Defining the graph model

msg.data:
Starting from that schema we will construct a graph model just like this:



We have 4 nodes:

  • Beat (police district) with a beat property;
  • Crime with id, description, case_number, point properties;
  • CrimeType with primary_type property;
  • CrimeDate with parsed_date

And 3 relationships:

  • ON_BEAT starting from a Beat and ending in a Crime;
  • IS_TYPE starting from a Crime and ending in a CrimeType;
  • ON_DATE starting from a Crime and ending in a CrimeDate;

paragraphs.title: Add new columns to the dataset
paragraphs.text: val exendedCrimeDF = crimeDF.withColumn("parsed_date", concat_ws("", split(substring(crimeDF("date"), 0, 10), "-"))).withColumn("point", concat_ws(", ", crimeDF("latitude"), crimeDF("longitude")))

paragraphs.title: Defining some constraints in order to speed up the import process
paragraphs.text:
%neo4j
CREATE CONSTRAINT ON (b:Beat) ASSERT b.beat IS UNIQUE

%neo4j
CREATE CONSTRAINT ON (c:Crime) ASSERT c.id IS UNIQUE

%neo4j
CREATE CONSTRAINT ON (ct:CrimeType) ASSERT ct.primary_type IS UNIQUE

%neo4j
CREATE CONSTRAINT ON (cd:CrimeDate) ASSERT cd.parsed_date IS UNIQUE

paragraphs.title: Let's import the Data as Graph into Neo4j by using the Neo4j-Spark-Connetor
paragraphs.text:
import org.neo4j.spark._

//Nodes
val beat = ("Beat", Seq("beat")) // Beat node, with beat property
val crime = ("Crime", Seq("id", "description", "case_number", "point")) // Crime node with id, description, case_number, point properties
val crimeType = ("CrimeType", Seq("primary_type")) // CrimeType node with primary_type property
val crimesDates = ("CrimeDate", Seq("parsed_date")) // CrimeDate node with parsed_date property

//Relationships
val on_beat = ("ON_BEAT", Seq.empty) // ON_BEAT relationship starting from a Beat and ending in a Crime
val is_type = ("IS_TYPE", Seq.empty) // IS_TYPE relationship starting from a Crime and ending in a CrimeType
val on_date = ("ON_DATE", Seq.empty) // ON_DATE relationship starting from a Crime and ending in a CrimeDate

/*
 * Neo4jDataFrame provides `mergeEdgeList(sc: SparkContext, dataFrame: DataFrame, source: (label,Seq[prop]), relationship: (type,Seq[prop]), target: (label,Seq[prop]))` to merge a DataFrame back into a Neo4j graph
 * - both nodes are merged by first propery in sequence, all the others will be set on the entity, relat
 * - relationships are merged between the two nodes and all properties from sequence will be set on the relationship
 * - property names from the sequence are used as column names for the data-frame, currently there is no name translation
 * - the result are sent in batches of 10000 to the graph 
 */
Neo4jDataFrame.mergeEdgeList(sc, exendedCrimeDF, beat, on_beat, crime)
Neo4jDataFrame.mergeEdgeList(sc, exendedCrimeDF, crime, is_type, crimeType)
Neo4jDataFrame.mergeEdgeList(sc, exendedCrimeDF, crime, on_date, crimesDates)

paragraphs.title: Let's query the graph directly from Zeppelin!
paragraphs.text:
%neo4j
MATCH (crime:Crime)-[is:IS_TYPE]->(type:CrimeType),
    (crime)-[on:ON_DATE]->(date:CrimeDate)
RETURN crime, is, type, on, date
limit 10
